I am not an arborist or forester, I'm an engineer who loves trees and have spent lots of time talking to experts about how to best manage forests. Most of my tree exploration has centered around the South, so I do not fully understand the issues in the West.

What if we change the public discussion around this topic, and instead or more articles that heavily emphasizes the emotional response, what if they explored scientific prevention using prescribed burns?

Large out of control fires are bad
Could controlled fires be good?
üßµ https://t.co/Xfz9BwbYg5

My worry is that when we only view fire as BAD, (I did most of my life because of Smokey's messaging) are we actually doing more damage? What if we leaned into the science and used periodic prescribed burns as a preventative tool to remove excess fuel from the forest floor?

I'm sad that the historic buildings were destroyed.

One reason I've heard scientists say fires may be burning hotter and more out of control is the underbrush and litter on the forest floor are providing more fuel, creating hotter fires which are more difficult to control.

üßµ

I finished my speech that night by saying, ‚ÄúMi casa es su casa.‚Äù My house is your house. It was true then, and it‚Äôs true now. My hope is that once we are through the pandemic (and that day will come!) everyone has the opportunity to visit. It truly is a magical place.

To be a part of something that had never happened before that night was not lost on this lover of history. I became the first woman to have a major sports venue named in her honor. More of this, please!
And what many people do not know is that the center is open to the public for play except during the US Open. Indeed, it is set within Corona Park.

With Ilana, my mother, & Ilana‚Äôs mother Ruth beside me & on the anniversary of Dr. Martin Luther King, Junior‚Äôs ‚ÄúI Have a Dream‚Äù speech (about which I was thrilled) I felt so honored this center, one of the largest public tennis facilities in the world, would have my name on it.

It had been raining the entire day. And 30 minutes before the ceremony was to begin, it stopped. I often think my father, who had passed away in June, played a part in that. The night was incredibly special.

On this night 14 years ago, August 28, 2006, I experienced one of the greatest honors of my life when the USTA National Tennis Center, home of the @usopen, was renamed the @usta Billie Jean King National Tennis Center.

I do not know the struggles of minorities in the USA who are misgendered or are discriminated. And instead of dismissing a term that‚Äôs not really designed for me and my feelings to begin with, I would rather hear them out. /5

The Filipino-Australian community has every right to claim the word, especially if there‚Äôs a sense of identification and a feeling of inclusivity. I‚Äôm now part of this community, and even though I still avoid using the word Filo, I allow people to use the word as they please. /4

When I moved to Australia, I didn‚Äôt like the word Filo at all. It didn‚Äôt mean anything to me and it sounded pretentious. Filipino is just as easy to pronounce and understand. But I learned that the term has been embraced for many years by Australians with Filipino ancestry. /3

Having said that, I don‚Äôt think I have the right to object on the term Filipinx as (1) I‚Äôm not part of the Filipino-American diaspora and (2) have no personal view about the struggles of minorities/women/LGBT in the US-context, more so the gender debates among academics there. /2

Philippines adopted gendered nouns from the Spanish (doktor/doktora, abogado/abogada) but the precolonial versions of our languages had no gender (manggagamot, manananggol). And since today the word Filipina exists, one can't completely claim Filipino is a gender-neutral term. /1
Also noticed that a short snow scene in the movie was an exact replica of one of the major sequences in ETERNAL SUNSHINE OF THE SPOTLESS MIND (another Kaufman masterpiece)
And yes, I don't think enough praises have been said about the versatility of Toni Collette.

Like his film SYNECDOCHE, NEW YORK, the themes are evident but seemingly don't demand to be verbalised. Dialogues and references are as profound, pretentious, or silly as the audience wants them to be; Kaufman's storytelling is always an unusual mix of certainty and uncertainty.
The works of Charlie Kaufman don't take you to other worlds but take you to other people's minds. I'M THINKING OF ENDING THINGS is a sad and disorienting ode to genius, memory, and being.

@eannaoc @KeohaneDan @wef Yes, lots of moving parts. It is the case that we spend more abroad than visitors spend here.

@decjordan @powerian Yes, that is true and Irish people don't really go on holidays in Irish cities.  But for Balance of Payments it doesn't have to be spent on domestic tourism services - just not spent while abroad (an import). @davecoghlan @centralbank_ie Not sure I'd term them favourable.  It'd be better all round if people were able/willing to get out & spend the money.  Yes, Irish households have been saving since the GFC but the current surge in savings is not by design. Still, does indicate lack of demand is not the problem.

The swings in the net position of Central Bank of Ireland vis √° vis commercial banks have been remarkable.

From pretty much zero during the early 2000s; to providing ‚Ç¨180bn of liquidity (including ELA) in late 2010; through the unwinding to taking ‚Ç¨50bn of excess deposits now. https://t.co/oALiXCDDCT

@crowleymjp @RayMinehane Yes.  And with interest rates essentially zero many people seem to be just leaving money in current accounts.

@RayMinehane Think many would prefer to have their old life back.

@jeandixelles @centralbank_ie within the data it can be seen that the biggest increase in deposits has been in current accounts.  So not especially a conscious decision to increase savings but more the outcome of the times we find ourselves in. But will we keep it there or go on a splurge?

@kjoc Yes, lots of countries are seeing higher household savings.  For most countries the drop in spending (due to combination of government restrictions and consumer caution) has been greater than the drop in income. On aggregate.

@RayMinehane Think it's mainly pretty typical households right around the country.  Many households have seen their income remain pretty stable but opportunities to spend it reduced (no pubs, restaurants, foreign travel etc.). Income steady plus spending down equals higher deposits.

@PadraigMacA That has likely had an impact in recent years alright.  First-time-buyers are were drawing down 20,000 loans a year as we entered the pandemic (up from 5,000 in 2012) so they are being used. It isn't a factor in the recent increase though.

@jeandixelles @centralbank_ie Yes, have been keeping an eye on that but the increases seem moderate enough.  By the end of July they had increased by ‚Ç¨0.5 billion since the start of the year.  Still it is another ‚Ç¨20 billion or so of household deposits on top of what the banking data show.
@antooconnell @centralbank_ie Maybe in the August figures. The data released today is for the end of July.  Those local lockdowns came a few days later.

@eannaoc Yes, for some products the output of Whitegate can exceed domestic needs. And the surplus is exported.

@RoryHearne Yes, that's it.  Would think age would be a significant factor.  Older people in each of the quintiles are likely to have greater amounts of deposits. Not a surprise really. They've had longer to repay debt/build up savings.

And what are banks doing with all this excess funding?  They are putting it on deposit with the central bank itself.

Domestic banks had ‚Ç¨30 billion on deposit with the central bank at the end of July. https://t.co/GnclfGnhiC

In aggregate terms we now have a domestic banking sector where private sector deposits significantly exceed private sector loans - a reverse of the mid-2000s position.

A gap which was ‚Ç¨52 billion in Dec 2019 widened to one of ‚Ç¨76 billion by the end of July. https://t.co/Rzefb4jX2t

Looking at businesses we see that deposits from businesses have also been significantly increasing - likely linked to uncertainty and caution.

Since the start of the year business deposits are up ‚Ç¨7 billion. https://t.co/IrEsrpfH6U

On the other side of the balance sheet, household transactions for loans have also changed.

In the last few months, repayments on household loans (all types) have significantly exceeded new drawdowns (& interest additions).  This is even with payment holidays on some mortgages. https://t.co/XetgUtz3wj

At the end of July, household deposits with @centralbank_ie regulated banks & credit unions reached ‚Ç¨120bn - record high.

What treasury yields actually reflect, and the logistical nightmare of replacing the Dollar as a reserve currency.

https://t.co/gIK3taSZWp

At some point the dollar may no longer be the reserve currency, that‚Äôs very true.  But it will take a ton of work on the part of every major country in the world to get there.

And they move slow.

Like‚Ä¶ that‚Äôs just not gonna sneak up on us‚Ä¶
20/

So when people talk about the dollar losing reserve status, think about the time component there.

Think about what's involved.

Think about how long it will take to replicate the biggest futures market in the world.

For slow moving actors like countries to re-hedge.
19/

Today, China said ‚Äúwe are selling a bunch of our future money for now money‚Äù - now, what does that mean?  It means they were GDP-hedged into the future, and they‚Äôre un-hedging to get money now.

How interesting is that?
18/

The US treasury market is the world‚Äôs biggest futures market.

By orders of magnitude.

So when you see news about the dollar or treasuries, try to think about what it means in this context because it makes more sense sometimes.
17/

Part of the reason the dollar is the reserve currency is because the UST market is massive.

Big and liquid enough to let **all the countries in the world** arbitrage **their entire future GDPs** on a near constant basis.

Think about that.
16/

Which is why the Fed/Banks have an incentive to keep the curve relatively flat until we‚Äôre out of the woods - they don‚Äôt want people being incentivized to store money when the economy is somewhat starved for it at the moment.
15/

But sometimes the future price of oil is lower - people need oil more now than they do in a year.  This disincentivizes storage and pushes supply into the market.

Money works the same:  low yields push money into the market now.
14/

This happens in futures markets too:  if the future price of oil is high relative to now, this is a way of incentivizing people to store it.

Similarly, if the yield on USTs is high, this incentivizes people to ‚Äústore money‚Äù (which we call saving).
13/

Money is generally more useful ‚Äúright now,‚Äù which is kinda where the yield comes from:  generally someone (with USTs it‚Äôs the government) will pay you a small fee to use money right now, and give it to you later.
12/

The Treasury market isn‚Äôt about companies (except maybe the very biggest) as much as it is about countries.

Countries produce LOTS of goods and services, they use the treasury market to de-risk their future GDP the way bread-makers de-risk future bread production.
11/

Just like wheat can get more expensive in the future, money can get more expensive in the future.  When you‚Äôre running a massive business this starts to matter a bit.

Now imagine running a country.
10/

Treasuries do pay a yield, yes, but when they mature they turn back into money.

So they‚Äôre really ‚Äúfuture money,‚Äù so in a way ‚ÄòDecember-maturing Treasuries‚Äô are to a business paying Christmas bonuses what ‚ÄúDecember wheat‚Äù is to the bread producer.
9/

So:  what about the price of money itself?

Let‚Äôs say I have $100M in my business account, but only use about $10M per quarter.

Since dollars are *the* world money, I can ‚Äúlock in the future price of money,‚Äù buying treasuries along the curve, just like specific month wheat
8/

When suppliers and producers can use these markets to create stable P&Ls for their business, it‚Äôs very pro-business.

If you‚Äôve ever run a P&L, perhaps you can imagine how awful it‚Äôd be if your costs or revenues fluctuated hugely during the year.
7/

And if I‚Äôm making bread and need wheat, I can buy a December delivery at a fixed price knowing I won‚Äôt have to pay more if the price goes up.

I miss out if the price drops but again: stability is worth more

These dynamics are a big part of why markets are good for society
6/

First, they allow *producers* to lock in a delivery price.

Like, they can sell 100 contracts for December wheat and then run their business knowing they‚Äôll get that price.

If wheat goes up they miss out on upside, but stability is worth more when you‚Äôre a farmer.
5/

In commodities markets, there is no singular ‚Äúprice of oil‚Äù - there is a ‚Äúprice of oil at a specific date.‚Äù  This is the futures market, and most of us only see/live in the ‚Äònow‚Äô part of it.

But there‚Äôs a lot more going on, and futures are kinda the whole point of markets.
4/

For many UST holders, especially big ones, the Treasury market is not about yields -- it‚Äôs a futures market for money.

To unpack that a bit, let‚Äôs talk about how futures markets work for a sec.
3/

This can apply to all sorts of things:

Tech stuff (old polaroid printer)
Bath stuff (hairdryer I have never used)
Appliances (an old tea kettle)
Office stuff (stationary and notebooks that have never been written on)
Clothing (you can only wear one shit at a time)

#declutter

If you have not used something for over a year you probably don't need it anymore and should get rid of it.

Even if it was expensive.

Sometimes even if it was sentimental.

#declutter
